  "articleSummary": "The article argues that teams can speed up early feature development by starting with a simple key-value (KV) store (e.g., Redis, S3) instead of immediately reaching for SQL or MongoDB. The core thesis is that KV patterns reduce schema churn and leverage optimized key lookups, making them suitable for data accessed by unique IDs, hierarchical or graph structures, and massive scale. The piece uses a persuasive, tutorial-like tone and employs metaphors like \"KV as Graphs & Trees\" and composite keys mimicking REST URLs. It targets software developers and tech leads, advising them to avoid KV when they need JOINs, property-based queries, or unbounded datasets.",
